<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-001-461 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 614 320</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Dec 11 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>MCI speaks against New Jersey deregulation. (MCI CommunicationsCorp.'s Donna Sorgi)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   MCI Communications Corp. (Officials and employees)New Jersey Bell Telephone Co. (Laws, regulations, etc.)andO;American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (Laws, regulations, etc.).andO;Ticker:    MCIC.andO;Topic:     CompetitionGovernment RegulationDeregulationNew JerseyTelephone companiesNew Jersey. Legislature. Senate.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MCI Speaks Against New Jersey Deregulation 12/11/91 TRENTON, NEW JERSEY,U.S.A., 1991 DEC 11 (NB) -- MCI, which failed in its attempt to stop apartial deregulation of Michigan's phone networks, is now trying to head offthe same train in New Jersey.andM;Donna Sorgi, MCI's director of regulatory and government affairs, said intestimony before the New Jersey State Senate that a bill to deregulate NewJersey Bell and ATandamp;T operations within the state should not be passed&quot;without clear and rigorous guidelines to ensure against monopoly abuse.&quot;andM;Control of the New Jersey legislature passed in the November elections fromDemocrats to Republicans, over tax issues.andP;  Republicans, who have more than atwo-thirds majority in both Houses, will take office in January.andP;  Jersey Belland ATandamp;T, which had spent time and money trying to influence the Democrats,are now keen to pass legislation before the Republicans take over.andM;But Sorgi's statement indicated that the bill presently before thelegislature goes too far, and would let New Jersey Bell subsidize competitiveoperations on the backs of local ratepayers, illegally driving businessesoutside telecommunications out of business.andM;Sorgi also indiciated that, if ATandamp;T operations within the state arederegulated, it could drive companies like hers out of the state through useof its monopoly power -- the company controls about 65 percent of the longdistance market.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19911211/Press Contact: Frank J. Walter, MCI, 914-933-6292)</TEXT></DOC>